{"questionId":"22683","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>In a city, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>32</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of people have blue eyes. If someone has blue eyes, the probability that they&nbsp;also have fair hair is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>58</mn><mo>%</mo></math>. This information is represented in the following tree diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/019743f2b8de67f003d3dd307df98bfc4b329e42.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>It is known that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>41</mn><mo>%</mo></math> of people in this city have fair hair.</p>\n<p>Calculate the value of</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>32</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>68</mn><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for setting up equation for fair-haired or equivalent.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>33</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22683","referenceCode":"21N.1.SL.TZ0.11c.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"b.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.5—Probability concepts, expected numbers","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4